Across subSahara Africa, the marital milieu has changed markedly in the past five decades [18] with women now delaying marriage and many entering relationships without the expectation that marriage will be the next step in live. In such a context, planning for divorce at the time of marriage is paradoxical. Women may have limited experience understanding that divorce as a potential plan of action in the context of marriage with may impact upon their willingness to plan for divorce from a young age. A second possible explanation for low levels of premarital planning for divorce is that it may be
partially culturally specific. On one hand, it has been queried if divorce is pragmatically preferable for women given the negative social and political repercussions of divorce stated in healthcare legislation and professional discourse [19-21]. Furthermore, it has been observed that a higher percentage of single children live with their mothers in developing countries compared to the local population in Houston, Texas [22]. Such findings imply broader challenges for single mothers. On the other hand, marriage has started to decline [23] with approximately 51 per cent of women reporting that they are no longer married in 2010 according to the Gabonese national census. As marital status becomes less associated with standard ways of leading life, it may become more acceptable for women to consider divorce as an effective strategy for coping in the event of problematic unions.
